[[ja:金山彦神]]
[[Image:Descendants of Izanami alone.svg|thumb|right|200px|Gods born from Izanami's illness and death (based on the ''Kojiki'') [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Creation_myths_of_Japan_4.svg View in SVG (supported browsers only)]]]
'''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神 (神道)}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話}}. Some theories suggest he is the father of {{ill|Amatsukunitama-no-Mikoto|ja|天津国玉神}}.

== Overview ==
In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}'', he is referred to as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山毘古神), while in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'', he is written as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神). He forms a divine pair with {{ill|Kanayamahime-no-Kami|ja|金山毘売神}} (also known as Kanayamahime-no-Kami, 金山姫神)<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Kanayamahiko-no-Kami – Kokugakuin University Kojiki Study Center Website |url=http://kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp/shinmei/kanayamabikonokami/ |website=kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp |access-date=2022-10-10 |publisher={{ill|Kokugakuin University|ja|國學院大學}}}}</ref>. The term "Kanayama" is generally interpreted as referring to a mine<ref name=":0" />, and the deities Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are understood as gods of metal and mining<ref name=":0" />.

According to the myth of {{ill|Kamiumi|ja|神産み}} ("divine birth"), Kanayamahiko-no-Kami was born from the vomit of {{ill|Izanami|ja|イザナミ}} when she suffered burns and fell ill after giving birth to the fire god {{ill|Kagu-tsuchi|ja|カグツチ}}<ref name=":0" />. In the ''Kojiki'', both Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are said to have been born this way, while in the ''Nihon Shoki'' (Third Alternate Writing), only Kanayamahiko-no-Kami is mentioned<ref name=":0" />.

Kanayamahiko-no-Kami is enshrined in shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Nangū Taisha|ja|南宮大社}} (dedicated solely to Kanayamahiko-no-Kami) in {{ill|Tarui, Gifu|ja|垂井町}}, {{ill|Nangu Otabi Shrine|ja|南宮御旅神社}} (dedicated solely to Kanayamahime-no-Kami), {{ill|Kanayago Shrine|ja|金屋子神社}} in {{ill|Yasugi, Shimane|ja|安来市}}, {{ill|Koganeyama Shrine (Ishinomaki)|ja|黄金山神社 (石巻市)}} on {{ill|Kinkasan|ja|金華山 (宮城県)}} in {{ill|Ishinomaki, Miyagi|ja|石巻市}}, {{ill|Mikane Shrine|ja|御金神社}} in {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都市}}, and {{ill|Hari Shrine|ja|針神社}}, a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Hataeda Hachiman Shrine|ja|幡枝八幡宮}}.

