In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}'', he is referred to as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山毘古神), while in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}'', he is written as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神). He forms a divine pair with {{ill|Kanayamahime-no-Kami|ja|金山毘売神|12=draft}} (also known as Kanayamahime-no-Kami, 金山姫神)<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Kanayamahiko-no-Kami – Kokugakuin University Kojiki Study Center Website |url=http://kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp/shinmei/kanayamabikonokami/ |website=kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp |access-date=2022-10-10 |publisher={{ill|Kokugakuin University|ja|國學院大學|12=draft}}}}</ref>. The term "Kanayama" is generally interpreted as referring to a mine<ref name=":0" />, and the deities Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are understood as gods of metal and mining<ref name=":0" />.

