[[ja:金山彦神]]
[[sn:Kanayama-hiko and Kanayama-hime]]

[[Image:Descendants of Izanami alone.svg|thumb|right|200px|Gods born from Izanami's illness and death (based on the ''Kojiki'') [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Creation_myths_of_Japan_4.svg View in SVG (supported browsers only)]]]
'''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神 (神道)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/deity|qq=}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese mythology|qq=}}. Some theories suggest he is the father of {{ill|Amatsukunitama-no-Mikoto|ja|天津国玉神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsukunitama-no-Mikoto|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}'', he is referred to as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山毘古神), while in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}'', he is written as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神). He forms a divine pair with {{ill|Kanayamahime-no-Kami|ja|金山毘売神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanayamahime-no-Kami|qq=}} (also known as Kanayamahime-no-Kami, 金山姫神)<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Kanayamahiko-no-Kami – Kokugakuin University Kojiki Study Center Website |url=http://kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp/shinmei/kanayamabikonokami/ |website=kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp |access-date=2022-10-10 |publisher={{ill|Kokugakuin University|ja|國學院大學|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokugakuin University|qq=}}}}</ref>. The term "Kanayama" is generally interpreted as referring to a mine<ref name=":0" />, and the deities Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are understood as gods of metal and mining<ref name=":0" />.

According to the myth of {{ill|Kamiumi|ja|神産み|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiumi|qq=}} ("divine birth"), Kanayamahiko-no-Kami was born from the vomit of {{ill|Izanami|ja|イザナミ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|qq=}} when she suffered burns and fell ill after giving birth to the fire god {{ill|Kagu-tsuchi|ja|カグツチ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagu-tsuchi|qq=}}<ref name=":0" />. In the ''Kojiki'', both Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are said to have been born this way, while in the ''Nihon Shoki'' (Third Alternate Writing), only Kanayamahiko-no-Kami is mentioned<ref name=":0" />.

Kanayamahiko-no-Kami is enshrined in shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Nangū Taisha|ja|南宮大社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nangū Taisha|qq=}} (dedicated solely to Kanayamahiko-no-Kami) in {{ill|Tarui, Gifu|ja|垂井町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tarui, Gifu|qq=}}, {{ill|Nangu Otabi Shrine|ja|南宮御旅神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nangu Otabi Shrine|qq=}} (dedicated solely to Kanayamahime-no-Kami), {{ill|Kanayago Shrine|ja|金屋子神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanayago Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Yasugi, Shimane|ja|安来市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasugi, Shimane|qq=}}, {{ill|Koganeyama Shrine (Ishinomaki)|ja|黄金山神社 (石巻市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koganeyama Shrine (Ishinomaki)|qq=}} on {{ill|Kinkasan|ja|金華山 (宮城県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinkasan|qq=}} in {{ill|Ishinomaki, Miyagi|ja|石巻市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishinomaki, Miyagi|qq=}}, {{ill|Mikane Shrine|ja|御金神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikane Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto|qq=}}, and {{ill|Hari Shrine|ja|針神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hari Shrine|qq=}}, a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Hataeda Hachiman Shrine|ja|幡枝八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hataeda Hachiman Shrine|qq=}}.

