[[Image:Descendants of Izanami alone.svg|thumb|right|200px|Gods born from Izanami's illness and death (based on the ''Kojiki'') [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Creation_myths_of_Japan_4.svg View in SVG (supported browsers only)]]]
'''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神) is a {{ill|Kami|en|Kami|qid=Q524158|lt=Deity|1=Kami}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|en|Japanese mythology|qid=Q814158|lt=Japanese mythology|1=Japanese mythology}}. Some theories suggest he is the father of {{ill|Amatsukunitama-no-Mikoto|ja|天津国玉神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsukunitama-no-Mikoto|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|en|Kojiki|qid=Q813031|lt=Kojiki|1=Kojiki}}'', he is referred to as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山毘古神), while in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|en|Nihon Shoki|qid=Q813935|lt=Nihon Shoki|1=Nihon Shoki}}'', he is written as '''Kanayamahiko-no-Kami''' (金山彦神). He forms a divine pair with {{ill|Kanayama-hiko and Kanayama-hime|lt=Kanayama-hiko and Kanayama-hime|lt=Kanayamahime-no-Kami|ja|金山毘売神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanayamahime-no-Kami|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 金山彦神}} (also known as Kanayamahime-no-Kami, 金山姫神)<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Kanayamahiko-no-Kami – Kokugakuin University Kojiki Study Center Website |url=http://kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp/shinmei/kanayamabikonokami/ |website=kojiki.kokugakuin.ac.jp |access-date=2022-10-10 |publisher={{ill|Kokugakuin University|en|Kokugakuin University|qid=Q495330|lt=Kokugakuin University|1=Kokugakuin University}}}}</ref>. The term "Kanayama" is generally interpreted as referring to a mine<ref name=":0" />, and the deities Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are understood as gods of metal and mining<ref name=":0" />.

According to the myth of {{ill|Kamiumi|en|Kamiumi|qid=Q3545159|lt=Kamiumi|1=Kamiumi}} ("divine birth"), Kanayamahiko-no-Kami was born from the vomit of {{ill|Izanami|en|Izanami|qid=Q682306|lt=Izanami|1=Izanami}} when she suffered burns and fell ill after giving birth to the fire god {{ill|Kagu-tsuchi|en|Kagu-tsuchi|qid=Q1640658|lt=Kagu-tsuchi|1=Kagu-tsuchi}}<ref name=":0" />. In the ''Kojiki'', both Kanayamahiko-no-Kami and Kanayamahime-no-Kami are said to have been born this way, while in the ''Nihon Shoki'' (Third Alternate Writing), only Kanayamahiko-no-Kami is mentioned<ref name=":0" />.

Kanayamahiko-no-Kami is enshrined in shrines across Japan, including {{ill|Nangū Taisha|en|Nangū Taisha|qid=Q704967|lt=Nangū Taisha|1=Nangū Taisha}} (dedicated solely to Kanayamahiko-no-Kami) in {{ill|Tarui, Gifu|en|Tarui, Gifu|qid=Q1345531|lt=Tarui, Gifu|1=Tarui, Gifu}}, {{ill|Nangu Otabi Shrine|ja|南宮御旅神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nangu Otabi Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Nangū Otabi Shrine|qid=Q11407720}} (dedicated solely to Kanayamahime-no-Kami), {{ill|Kanayago Shrine|ja|金屋子神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanayago Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in {{ill|Yasugi, Shimane|en|Yasugi, Shimane|qid=Q851114|lt=Yasugi, Shimane|1=Yasugi, Shimane}}, {{ill|Koganeyama Shrine (Ishinomaki)|ja|黄金山神社 (石巻市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koganeyama Shrine (Ishinomaki)|qq=}} on {{ill|Kinkasan|en|Kinkasan|qid=Q6413909|lt=Kinkasan|1=Kinkasan}} in {{ill|Ishinomaki|en|Ishinomaki|qid=Q270814|lt=Ishinomaki, Miyagi|1=Ishinomaki}}, {{ill|Mikane Shrine|ja|御金神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikane Shrine|1=Mikane Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11489342}} in {{ill|Kyoto|en|Kyoto|qid=Q34600|lt=Kyoto|1=Kyoto}}, and {{ill|Hari Shrine|ja|針神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hari Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Hataeda Hachiman Shrine|ja|幡枝八幡宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hataeda Hachiman Shrine|1=Hataeda-hachimangu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q43594565}}.

